Photos of the Japanese army in China during the 
Signed on Japanese war in 1937. Oh yeah, this is

29:10.351 --> 29:13.754
incredible. These pictures are too horrible for 
publication.

29:21.342 --> 29:32.855
If you wish to reproduce these pictures or use them 
for propaganda purposes in the division, they

29:21.342 --> 29:32.855
should prove very useful in rousing the wrath of 
any right-minded young American against such

29:21.342 --> 29:32.855
barbaric actions. However, I would prefer not to 
have my name associated with them in any way. When

29:39.588 --> 29:46.257
you have made whatever slides or copies you may 
need for your purposes, please give back the

29:39.588 --> 29:46.257
originals to Mrs. Price. Charles F.B. Price. He 
was my general. He was your general? Of the Samoan

29:52.666 --> 29:56.992
Defense Force after General Austin left. There's 
some of the pictures we had, but we did get these

29:57.012 --> 30:01.378
pictures and get them out to the troops. You 
understand that? Oh, you did. You're damn right we

30:03.701 --> 30:04.883
did. to show the brutality of the Japanese.

30:11.807 --> 30:15.671
I don't think you want that, maybe you do, maybe you 
don't. These are incredible. If you want them, you

30:18.655 --> 30:23.460
can take them and reproduce them and send them 
back. Maybe you don't want

30:23.480 --> 30:28.005
them. But those are all the things I had to do. Yeah. 
Give me that, put that down. Those are all the

30:32.951 --> 30:35.173
things they charged me with. You understand? 
Sure. G2 people and all like that. If I say you could

30:39.415 --> 30:43.520
sit in and talk, you'd say, well, you could just be 
blowing smoke up your ass. It's been passed.

30:44.982 --> 30:46.244
You're 87 and a half years old. You're ready to meet 
the maker. What the hell are you? You know? That's

30:51.170 --> 30:52.992
the brutality of the Japanese. And so you'd give 
those pictures... We had them produced and passed

30:53.373 --> 30:58.800
around into divisions. And another reason why...

31:06.068 --> 31:24.647
The Marines didn't want to have taken Jap 
prisoners because in Guadalcanal,

31:06.068 --> 31:24.647
when we made a reconnaissance in force, I wasn't 
there, but Frank Getchie, who was a great football

31:06.068 --> 31:24.647
player, he was in charge of this reconnaissance in 
force. And they underestimated the amount of

31:24.667 --> 31:29.491
resistance they'd get. And 22 of those people were 
wiped out, or maybe 40. And when the Marines went

31:35.414 --> 31:42.646
there to find him, the Japanese had cut the penises 
off of every Marine and stuck it in his mouth. And

31:43.988 --> 31:48.115
after the Marines knew that and heard that, they 
wouldn't take any Japanese prisoners. So we had a

31:48.135 --> 31:52.602
hard time prevailing on Marines to bring in 
prisoners for intelligence service. That's

31:53.624 --> 31:54.426
true. That was at Guadalcanal? That was at 
Guadalcanal. I lost a lot of friends there.

32:12.016 --> 32:15.021
You were speaking about race a minute. Cut it off

32:15.121 --> 32:18.806
now. Tell me, when was this written? Do you 
remember? 1941, I imagine. Where were you when it

32:28.621 --> 32:29.983
was written? Camp Elliot under General Vogel. 
Okay, 1941. And it hired me to hang it tight in the

32:34.630 --> 32:36.694
eye. They knew I did that.

32:42.239 --> 32:43.340
And who did you write it to? I wrote that to the Chief 
of Naval Operations.

32:51.511 --> 32:52.693
You've got the reply back. Okay, the reply's on the 
other side then. Said we wasn't sacrosanct. That

32:58.520 --> 33:00.603
means we had to, you know, fall in line. So what they 
did, they organized a lot of battalions and set

33:01.324 --> 33:04.748
them in the back areas. Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.

33:10.606 --> 33:14.951
But see, that's where your lawyer comes in and your 
civilian comes in in your service. He wouldn't

33:14.971 --> 33:17.054
dare ask a regular officer to do that. Of course, I 
never was treated as a reserve officer because I'd

33:19.357 --> 33:23.162
been a regular officer. You understand?

33:28.088 --> 33:29.069
So what has happened? You get Marcia Diane coming 
to this country and telling us you've got too many

33:29.970 --> 33:37.660
blacks in the service because they're mentally 
not mentally qualified.

33:40.019 --> 33:41.361
What do you think about that? I'm with him 100%. 
We've had some good black Marines. And I was

33:47.611 --> 33:54.141
sitting, they asked me... You can put this on tape. 
Put it on tape. I just turned it on right now. I was

33:57.226 --> 34:04.317
asked by a board at Camp Pendleton after the war 
what I felt about black personnel. And I said this,

34:05.358 --> 34:09.064
if we can train them properly... and they can hit 
the beach and bury the breast of the battle and die

34:09.888 --> 34:15.996
along with us, I'm for them 100%. But I don't 
believe in giving them anything on account of

34:17.217 --> 34:19.720
their color. Cut it. Cut this. You can edit any of 
this stuff off when I give you the transcript. All

34:26.889 --> 34:27.189
right. So let's just keep it on. Okay. You getting 
tired? No. All right. Let me see. Brutality of the

34:34.150 --> 34:36.293
Japs. I showed you that. And how, what the 
Americans, what did your friends and colleagues

34:37.695 --> 34:44.065
think? What did they think about having these 
prisoner of wars? And what did they think about, I

34:47.731 --> 34:51.977
mean, how did they treat them? The troops were 
never contacted. The only people contacted were

34:55.715 --> 35:00.980
the Marine guards, the Marines. How did the guards 
treat the prisoners? They treated them fairly.

35:07.867 --> 35:13.713
There was always an interpreter or a Marine who 
could speak Japanese with them. They didn't try to

35:13.733 --> 35:15.495
abuse anybody. The only abuse among Japanese was 
among themselves.

35:22.990 --> 35:24.231
You mean they abused each other? Yes. In what way? 
Well, they'd fight. They'd fight with each other?

35:29.117 --> 35:31.840
Sure, every now and then, but very seldom, very 
seldom. We had no trouble. We had no problem. And

35:34.964 --> 35:36.506
they got 1,200 calories a day? Those who worked got 
over that, 1,400 calories. Those who didn't work

35:40.551 --> 35:42.994
got less than 1,100 calories. There were very few 
of them that didn't work. The only ones that didn't

35:45.236 --> 35:49.261
work was that stockade out there with those 
officers. Why didn't they work? Because I was mad

35:50.022 --> 35:52.525
because I had to finish a guard out there. Why 
didn't they want to work? Well, because they

35:54.276 --> 35:55.698
didn't have to. They were officers.

36:00.843 --> 36:04.828
And we couldn't pay the prisoners like we were 
supposed to because there were too many of them.

36:04.848 --> 36:06.630
There wasn't a lot of them. Before prisoners were 
3,000. Now you had 30,000 or more. That's when it

36:11.215 --> 36:17.521
swelled when we took the garrison from Rota. Those 
people had been over there eating frogs and

36:17.541 --> 36:22.647
lizards and rats and everything else. We brought 
them over to Ireland, and we cleaned them all up,

36:22.998 --> 36:30.969
kept them there 15 to 20 days, and then sent them 
back to Japan. Gave them medical? You mean sent

36:34.413 --> 36:36.396
them back to Japan after the war? Yeah. Gave them 
medical? Yeah.

36:50.535 --> 36:51.857
And was the next job... And what was the next job?

37:48.217 --> 37:49.399
I'm trying to tell you. You wanted to see some of the 
Japanese. Has we got them in? Yeah.

37:58.493 --> 38:01.077
Were they real skinny and beat up? Hell no. I got a 
joke to tell on myself, too. Okay, tell me. On top of

38:06.807 --> 38:07.848
the...

38:13.036 --> 38:13.397
Uh...

38:19.081 --> 38:21.405
Well, I had headquarters call it Frog Roost. 
Pacific cemeteries, you don't see that.

38:39.536 --> 38:43.443
And up on, overlooking the Ganya Harbor. Mm-hmm. 
And I lived there with a fellow named Jim Lane, who

38:44.275 --> 38:50.684
was personnel down in the island command. And it 
was just a tent up on coconut logs with a floor in it.

38:55.510 --> 39:01.378
And the Navy stole the icebox and gave it to me for a 
favor. So in

39:01.499 --> 39:12.814
cleaning out during the assault phase, there were 
a lot of Japs tunneled up in these places and they

39:14.161 --> 39:20.486
thought they'd kill them all with the 
flamethrowers. But there were two of them still

39:20.506 --> 39:22.188
living. And I lived on top of them there for over 
eight months. And you didn't know they were living

39:28.113 --> 39:29.494
down there? I didn't know they were living under 
me. And we had a little old

39:31.416 --> 39:37.601
monkey shower there. We've got some pipe and we've 
got a little water and we had a shower and we built a

39:37.621 --> 39:43.746
little bib on the front of our tent And that's where 
we'd take a shower. So he was living off this water

39:45.959 --> 39:48.582
we'd take a shower with. So they liked to hurrah the 
hell out of me about that because we found him down

39:49.603 --> 40:01.058
on... And one day I hung up my utilities and I missed 
him. Well, I thought maybe the wind blew him away.

40:03.721 --> 40:10.510
But the Jap got him and he was down there on a dump at 
the officer's mess prowling around with his

40:03.721 --> 40:10.510
marine clothes on. And I never liked to live that 
down either, but they had my name in them. Oh,

40:14.819 --> 40:16.160
really? Son of a bitch. He stole your clothes and 
went down to the garbage dump? That's right. My

40:23.909 --> 40:26.091
name was in the back of them, right back in here. Was 
he wearing colonel patches? Was he wearing

40:30.096 --> 40:31.758
colonel insignias? Yeah, no, no, he wasn't 
wearing that. So they teased you about that, I bet.

40:37.904 --> 40:38.906
Oh, God, yes. Good day. We read the combat 
citation. I just wanted to show you a few pictures.

40:51.767 --> 40:52.569
Yellow leader. Promotions.

